ading is so new - indeed, it was all but created by Enron in the 1990s - tha=
t federal agencies will have to spend months finding out how rivals compete =
in order to develop guidelines to measure the merger's impact.=20
"We don't have any track record here," said Ernest Gellhorn, an antitrust ex=
pert at George Mason University.=20
The deal will be reviewed by state and federal agencies, but the most critic=
al approvals will come from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) =
and US antitrust agencies.=20
Central to the antitrust review will be how competition authorities define t=
he market - how big it is, which companies are included as competitors, and =
how the market share is divided up.=20
Former antitrust officials said Enron might be forced to resort to a "failin=
g firm" defence, which is occasionally used by companies with large market s=
hares when attempting to add to their dominant position.=20
But Robert McTamaney, an antitrust partner at Carter Ledyard & Milburn, said=
 the failing-firm route may be difficult for Dynegy and Enron to prove, sinc=
e it requires a showing that without the merger, Enron's trading business wo=
uld exit the market completely.=20
Helping the companies, however, is the relative ease with which competitors =
can enter the trading market, experts said.=20
An analysis of barriers will hinge on whether rivals can successfully argue =
that the level of expertise in the industry is so sophisticated - or that En=
ron's trading technologies are so specialised - that it would be impossible =
for new entrants to duplicate the company's operations.=20
